{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/ml-from-scratch-decision-tree-c6444102436a", "time": 1683013702.0640671, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/ml-from-scratch-decision-tree-c6444102436a/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "ML from Scratch (Decision Tree). Building Decision trees from scratch | by Abhinav Singh | Towards Data Science", "h1": "ML from Scratch (Decision Tree)", "description": "In this and a couple of upcoming articles, I\u2019ll try to explain classical machine learning algorithms from a code point of view. As I always feel if you can code a simple implementation of the ML\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["In this and a couple of upcoming articles, I\u2019ll try to explain classical machine learning algorithms from a code point of view. As I always feel if you can code a simple implementation of the ML algorithm then your understanding is solid.", "As this is the first post in ML from scratch series, I\u2019ll start with DT (Decision Tree) from the classification point of view as it is quite popular and simple to understand. The structure of this article is, first we will understand the building blocks of DT from both code and theory perspective, and then in end, we assemble these building blocks to form a simple DT which we will test on the Iris data-set.", "When building DT one of the most important selections is the criterion of splitting a node, though we a couple of choices we will use the Gini index for this demonstration.It is described as following,", "For a given node it is defined as", "so, after calculating the Gini index for left and right nodes we take a weighted average of left and right node and that becomes the Gini index of the parent node which will be used to split the node.", "i.e values in left node/total values in left and right node * gini impurity of left node + values in right node/total values in left and right node * gini impurity of right node", "As we have finished our split part, we will now move toward building a tree using this, for that we first create a function that will generate a new node given data.", "This function checks every value of every feature to find the best split value, we can also use the random split technique. After this all calculations it returns a node created using node class (full code mentioned on left).", "This function also checks for some other constraints like minimum Gini value i.e the node Gini value should be at least greater then minimum Gini value set by the user to continue split if not then the node is considered as a leaf node. It also checks for the minimum number of samples present i.e if the total data points present is less than the minimum samples then also node is considered as a leaf node.", "Let\u2019s now move Towards the build tree method, It builds a tree in a recursive manner. This function also uses some criterion for such as max depth - (set by the user to make sure we only built tree up to a certain depth)", "There is just one more method which is only to print the entire tree structure. Just an inorder traversal of the DT.", "So, We have now formulated all building blocks of DT now let\u2019s combine and try to understand the complete flow of the DT along with code.", "This simple implementation without changes to default parameters gives a whooping 95% accuracy. Although I did not check for overfitting and other issues as this article does not focus on that. Run it module by module, break it. Please let me know if there are any errors. Hope you guys have fun!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fc6444102436a&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ft